<span id="freeTextContainer16293981014679345857">â<i>Thereâs a moment when love makes us believe in death for the first time.</i>â <br/><br/>I read and noted the presumed truth of that line: the fear of losing those we love. Now I feel and live it. When a friend recently consoled me with the idea that grief is love with nowhere to go, I knew exactly what she meant.<br/><br/>This is a beautiful and profound novel that I ended up finishing at a painfully and unexpectedly (in)appropriate time. <br/><br/>Itâs about making a life after sudden death (âno one is born just onceâ), nurtur</span>
  <span id="freeText16293981014679345857" style="display:none">â<i>Thereâs a moment when love makes us believe in death for the first time.</i>â <br><br>I read and noted the presumed truth of that line: the fear of losing those we love. Now I feel and live it. When a friend recently consoled me with the idea that grief is love with nowhere to go, I knew exactly what she meant.<br><br>This is a beautiful and profound novel that I ended up finishing at a painfully and unexpectedly (in)appropriate time. <br><br>Itâs about making a life after sudden death (âno one is born just onceâ), nurturing memories, and living with ghosts (not literally). Itâs about the importance of stories: of piecing them together from fragments, whether the sort of snippets refugees abandon or treasure, or natural artefacts that the brave, wise, big-hearted geologist, Athos, studies. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1547418675i/26912343._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>Heart-shaped hole in pebbles</i> (<a href="http://www.legacy.com/news/advice-and-support/article/grief-after-a-long-goodbye" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>.)<br><br><b>One Story, Two Narrators</b><br><br>The first 200 exquisite pages are fictional poet Jakob Beerâs unfinished memoirs, âa biography of longingâ. All his writings were, in some sense, ghost stories, or about hiding. But this charts his being the sole survivor of a Nazi raid on his home, aged seven, then to Zakynthos, Toronto, and back to Zakynthos. Itâs profound, painful, poetic, and hopeful. It drips with symbolism and recurring tropes. It was <b>5*</b> at least.<br><br>Then, for the final 100 pages, it suddenly switches to Ben, the son of refugees, who âwas born into absenceâ¦ A hiding place, rotted out by griefâ to a father âwho erased himself as much as possible within the legal bounds of citizenshipâ. Ben was a student admirer of Jakob, who meets elderly Jakob once, at a party. When Jakob dies, Ben tries to assemble the pieces of his life story, travelling to Jakob's home on Zakynthos, living some parallels of his Jakob's life. The trouble is, Benâs voice is barely distinguishable from Jakobâs (even the chapter titles are taken from those in the main part). The only difference is that there are hardly any of the poetic aphorisms that make most of the book sublime. A hugely disappointing way to finish.<br><br><b>Living after Loss</b><br><br>â<i>There is no absence if there remains even the memory of absence.</i>â<br><br>Jakob lost his parents and older sister in terrifying circumstances. Piano-playing Bella is the strongest memory and hence greatest loss throughout his life. <br><br>"<i>She whispers; not for me to join her, but so that, when I'm close enough, she can push me back into the world.</i>â<br><br>He nurtures and cherishes his memories, the times he almost glimpses her, but gradually he learns the best remembrance is to embrace the life heâs privileged to have. Not to forget, but to focus more on the future than the past.<br><br>â<i>To remain with the dead is to abandon them.</i>"<br><br><b>Quotes about Loss</b><br><br>â¢	âTo survive was to escape fate. But if you escape your fate, whose life do you then step into?â<br><br>â¢	âThe intimacy that death forces on us.â Going through letters and possessions. <br><br>â¢	âA house, more than a diary, is the intimate glimpse. A house is a life interrupted.â<br><br>â¢	âMurder steals from a man his future. It steals from his own death. But it must not steal from him his life.â<br><br>â¢	âI tried to embroider darknessâ¦ Black on black, until the only way to see the texture would be to move the whole cloth under the light.â<br><br><b>Other Quotes</b><br><br>â¢	âLimestone - that crushed reef of memoryâ and cave formations âspasms in timeâ.<br><br>â¢	âFind a way to make beauty necessary; find a way to make necessity beautiful.â<br><br>â¢	âStarlight [is] only the white breath of an old cry. Sending their white messages millions of years, only to be crumpled up by the waves.â<br><br>â¢	âI long to steal your memories... to syphon off your dreams [nightmares].â<br><br>â¢	Writing about childhood memories âin a language foreign to their happeningâ¦ English could protect me; an alphabet without memory.â Translation as a form of transubstantiation.<br><br>â¢	âThe best teacher lodges an interest not in the mind, but in the heart.â<br><br>â¢	âOne could look deeply for meaning or one can invent it.â<br><br>â¢	âHistory is amoral: events occurred. But memory is moral; what we consciously remember is what our conscience remembersâ¦ History and memory share events; that is, they share time and space. Every moment is two moments.â<br><br>â¢	âThe leaves whisper under the street lampsâ¦ Flowers dripping from window boxes.â<br><br>â¢	âThe visitation of moonlight. It occupies the darkness, erasing everything it touches.â<br><br>â¢	âThe shipâs flag grabs at twilight. Heat washes away under the rushing fountain of stars.â<br><br><br>âWrite to save yourselfâ¦ and someday youâll write because youâve been saved.â<br>Hence this review. I hope. I do. And this book is part of that process. </span>
