<span id="freeTextContainer7821805355970718224">âI see that I must give what I most need.â<br/><br/>Itâs not easy to sustain a poetic voice for almost three hundred pages though Virginia Woolf managed it brilliantly for two hundred in The Waves. And as a result of this difficulty this wasnât always compelling. At times the writing is stunning and itâs brilliant how much poetry and pathos she manages to extract from everyday detail. At other times the unrelenting insistency on poetry felt a bit strained as if there was too much idealising going on.<br/>Itâs </span>
  <span id="freeText7821805355970718224" style="display:none">âI see that I must give what I most need.â<br /><br />Itâs not easy to sustain a poetic voice for almost three hundred pages though Virginia Woolf managed it brilliantly for two hundred in The Waves. And as a result of this difficulty this wasnât always compelling. At times the writing is stunning and itâs brilliant how much poetry and pathos she manages to extract from everyday detail. At other times the unrelenting insistency on poetry felt a bit strained as if there was too much idealising going on.<br />Itâs a novel that investigates separation and the mindâs struggles to create a continuity of wellbeing. Jakob manages to escape when his parents and sister are arrested by the Nazis. After months of hiding, often digging himself into holes in the landscape, he is rescued by a Greek archaeologist called Athos. Later it falls on an admirer of Jakob who becomes a poet to keep his and Athosâ memory alive. The book is narrated in the form of two journals and is a kind of archaeology of memory. <br />There are probably two hundred brilliant pages and another hundred of unnecessary upholstery. I couldnât help feeling this would have been a masterpiece if those other pages had been edited out. <br /></span>
