<div id="review_58043431" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/58043431" />
    <a title="Sherry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/193297-sherry"><img alt="Sherry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388868192p2/193297.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/58043431?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sherry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sherry" href="/user/show/193297-sherry">Sherry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780679454397" href="/book/show/998848.Fugitive_Pieces">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58043431" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2060412494478211556">I&apos;ve never had a complaint like this about a book I&apos;ve read: the language was too beautiful. I would come across a line like: &quot;I ran until the first light wrung the last greyness out of the stars, dripping dirty light between the trees&quot; and stop and marvel over it, and in doing so, I would lose track of what was going on. Each sentence is crafted like that. Each sentence is like a part of a poem, which makes sense, because Anne Michaels is a poet. But sometimes I just wanted the story to go on. </span>
  <span id="freeText2060412494478211556" style="display:none">I've never had a complaint like this about a book I've read: the language was too beautiful. I would come across a line like: "I ran until the first light wrung the last greyness out of the stars, dripping dirty light between the trees" and stop and marvel over it, and in doing so, I would lose track of what was going on. Each sentence is crafted like that. Each sentence is like a part of a poem, which makes sense, because Anne Michaels is a poet. But sometimes I just wanted the story to go on. <br /><br />I also was confused a bit by the form of the book. The main character kind of disappears two-thirds of the way in and we get to see him through a new, totally different character. I would have rather stayed with the first character. But I'm sure Michaels did that for a very good reason, I just felt a little bereft when the first character went into the background. I'm sure that was her point, because one of the themes of the book is people disappearing from your life. So she gave us a touch of that. I felt sad when the book was over, but I don't exactly know why. <br /><br />I might have given this five stars, except I think it was too beautiful. Isn't that strange?</span>
  <a data-text-id="2060412494478211556" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


